Introduction
This article is the second part of a two-part series designed to give you a strong foundation in Go. This article covers advanced Go concepts, including maps, structs, receiver functions, and interfaces.
Prerequisites
To continue this article, it is best to have a solid understanding of Go fundamentals. If you don't, let's start with part A of this series.
Let’s start…
Maps
Maps are an unordered collection of key-value pairs where the keys are unique. Values associated with a key can be updated, removed, or retrieved. The syntax below is used to define a map in the Go language.
map[KEY]VALIn the above syntax, KEY and VAL denote the types of its keys and values. All the keys specified in a map must have the same type, and all the values should have the same value type. However, the data types of the KEY and VAL do not need to have the same type.
Refer to the Go file 1 below for an example definition of a map.
// Go file 1
package mainimport "fmt"
func main() {
// method 1: map literal
// httpStatus map contains integer keys and string values
httpStatus := map[int]string{
200: "OK",
201: "Created",
404: "Not Found",
500: "Internal Server Error",
}
// method 2: the built-in make function
httpStatus2 := make(map[int]string)
httpStatus2[200] = "OK"
httpStatus2[201] = "Created"
httpStatus2[404] = "Not Found"
httpStatus2[500] = "Internal Server Error"
fmt.Println(httpStatus)
fmt.Println(httpStatus2)
}
As per Go file 1, both methods 1 and 2 can be used to define a map. Method 1 is preferred when the contents are known up front, while make is the choice when the map starts empty and is filled in as the program runs.
Map Operations
Once the map is defined, there are five operations that can be applied to it. In this section, assume m is our map.

• Retrieve: m[key] returns the value stored in the map against the key.

• Retrieve with existence check: value, isExists := m[key] returns a second boolean that reports whether the key was present.

• Insert/Update: m[key] = value Inserts the key-value pair if the key is new to the map. Otherwise, it will update (overwrite) the existing value against the key.

• Delete: delete(m,key) Deletes the entry from the map.

• Length: len(m) Returns the number of key-value pairs currently stored in the map.
Note: All these operations are safe. If the element is not in the map, a lookup will return the zero value for its type.
Maps fall into the reference type category in Go. Hence, we cannot take the memory address of a map. Also, assigning a map to another variable or passing it to a function does not copy the underlying data. Both names refer to the same map, and any change made to one is visible in the other.
Refer to the extended code below for Example 1 with the operations that we have discussed.
// Go file 2
package mainimport "fmt"
func main() {
// httpStatus map contains integer keys and string values
httpStatus := map[int]string{
200: "OK",
201: "Created",
404: "Not Found",
500: "Internal Server Error",
}
// using built-in make function to create a map
httpStatus2 := make(map[int]string)
httpStatus2[200] = "OK"
httpStatus2[201] = "Creat" //corrected later by the update operation
httpStatus2[404] = "Not Found"
httpStatus2[500] = "Internal Server Error"
// retrieve
var statusValue string = httpStatus2[200]
fmt.Println(statusValue)
// retrieve - key that not exist
statusValue = httpStatus2[202]
fmt.Println(statusValue)
// retrieve with existence check
statusValue, isExist := httpStatus2[203]
fmt.Println("key 203 exist: ", isExist, " value: ", statusValue)
statusValue, isExist = httpStatus2[201]
fmt.Println("key 201 exist: ", isExist, " value: ", statusValue)
// insert
httpStatus[401] = "Unauthorized"
// update - fixing the "Creat" typo
httpStatus[201] = "Created"
// traversing the map
traverseMap(httpStatus)
// delete
delete(httpStatus, 401)
// delete — a no-op when the key is absent
delete(httpStatus, 999)
// traversing the map again
traverseMap(httpStatus)
mapLength := len(httpStatus)
fmt.Println("length of httpStatus: ", mapLength)
}
func traverseMap(m map[int]string) {
fmt.Println("\nStart traversing the map....")
for key, value := range m {
fmt.Printf("Key: %v, Value: %v\n", key, value)
}
fmt.Println("Map traversal completed...")
fmt.Println()
}
Note: Two traversals print the keys in different orders. Go deliberately randomizes the order of map iterations between runs so that no program can come to depend on it.
Structs
Consider the data that describes a customer. It will contain several properties such asfirstName, lastName, email, and so on. Those properties may each have a different data type. A struct represents this kind of entity by aggregating several related attributes into a single value, and each data property within a struct is called a field.
Since a struct is a single value, it can be copied as one unit, passed to functions and returned by them, compared with other structs of the same type, and stored in arrays, slices, and maps. Refer to the struct definition syntax and the example below.
// struct
type <StructName> struct {
// define properties
}Example Struct…
// Go file 3
package mainimport (
"fmt"
"time"
)
// aggregates several customer related fields into a single entity
type Customer struct {
id int
firstName string
lastName string
postalAddress string
email string
mobile string
dateOfBirth time.Time
}
func main() {
// value of a struct type
var customer1 Customer = Customer{
id: 1,
firstName: "John",
lastName: "Doe",
email: "john@doe.com",
mobile: "123123123",
dateOfBirth: time.Date(1990, time.January, 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, time.UTC),
}
// printing entire struct literal
fmt.Printf("Customer 1 details: %+v\n", customer1)
// access an individual field of a struct literal
fmt.Printf("First Name: %s\n", customer1.firstName)
// structs and pointers
// the & operator takes the memory address of an individual field
fmt.Printf("Customer 1 First Name Address: %+v\n", namePtr)
fmt.Printf("Customer 1 First ID Address: %+v\n", idPtr)
// the * operator dereferences a pointer, retrieving the value stored there
fmt.Printf("Dereferenced Customer 1 First Name: %s\n", *namePtr)
fmt.Printf("Dereferenced Customer 1 ID: %d\n", *idPtr)
}
According to the example above, the Customer struct aggregates seven fields of three data types ( int, string, and time.Time) into a single entity. When defining struct fields, we do not put commas or semicolons at the end of each field. They are simply listed one per line.
After defining the Customer struct, it is used in the main() function to create a value called customer1. A value of a struct type is called a struct literal. fieldName: value, form is used to assign the value for each field of the struct. The postalAddress field is not assigned any value in the customer1 variable. Any field left out of a struct literal is automatically set to the zero value of the type.
As per Go’s variable names and visibility discussed in Part A, all the fields of the Customer struct are unexported. They are only visible within the same package. If you want to export outside the current package (main), define the field names starting with an uppercase letter. (Eg: FirstName).
To access an individual field of a struct literal, you can use the dot notation.
Structs with Pointers
It is possible to obtain the memory address of an individual struct field. In the Go file 3 above, the & operator is applied to customer1's firstName and id fields to produce pointers to them, and those pointers are then dereferenced with the * operator to retrieve the underlying values.
