Go supports object-oriented programming (OOP) differently. Since there is no universal definition of OOP, Go specifies an object as a simple value or variable that has methods. A method is a function associated with a particular type (Donovan and Kernighan, 2015).
Method Declarations
The method declarations are similar to the conventional function declaration with an extra parameter before the function name. That parameter attaches the function to the type of that parameter. Refer to the example Go file 4 below.
// Go file 4
package mainimport (
"fmt"
"time"
)
// customer struct
type Customer struct {
id int
firstName string
lastName string
postalAddress string
email string
mobile string
dateOfBirth time.Time
}
func main() {
var customer1 Customer = Customer{
id: 1,
firstName: "John",
lastName: "Doe",
email: "john@doe.com",
mobile: "123123123",
postalAddress: "Lake Avenue",
dateOfBirth: time.Date(1990, time.January, 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, time.UTC),
}
// calling a METHOD - the value comes first, joined by a dot,
// and is passed implicitly as the receiver
customer1.printCustomer()
// calling an ordinary FUNCTION - the value is passed explicitly
// as a normal argument. The output is identical
printCustomerFunc(customer1)
}
// printCustomer is a METHOD on the Customer type.
// (c Customer) is the receiver: an extra parameter written before the
// method name, which binds this function to the Customer type.
// c behaves like any other parameter and holds a COPY of the value
// the method was called on, so it cannot modify the original customer.
func (c Customer) printCustomer() {
var strPattern = "============================================================"
fmt.Println(strPattern)
fmt.Println("Customer Details ")
fmt.Println(strPattern)
fmt.Println()
// fields of the receiver are accessed through c, exactly as with
// any struct value
fmt.Printf("First Name: %s\n", c.firstName)
fmt.Printf("Last Name: %s\n", c.lastName)
fmt.Printf("Email: %s\n", c.email)
fmt.Printf("Mobile: %s\n", c.mobile)
fmt.Printf("Postal Address: %s\n", c.postalAddress)
fmt.Printf("DOB: %s\n", c.dateOfBirth)
fmt.Println(strPattern)
}
// printCustomerFunc is an ordinary FUNCTION that does exactly the same work.
// The only difference is that the Customer is declared as a normal parameter
// inside the parentheses after the name, rather than as a receiver before it,
// and so it belongs to no particular type
func printCustomerFunc(c Customer) {
var strPattern = "============================================================"
fmt.Println(strPattern)
fmt.Println("Customer Details (Using Conventional Function) ")
fmt.Println(strPattern)
fmt.Println()
fmt.Printf("First Name: %s\n", c.firstName)
fmt.Printf("Last Name: %s\n", c.lastName)
fmt.Printf("Email: %s\n", c.email)
fmt.Printf("Mobile: %s\n", c.mobile)
fmt.Printf("Postal Address: %s\n", c.postalAddress)
fmt.Printf("DOB: %s\n", c.dateOfBirth)
fmt.Println(strPattern)
}
Figure 2: Expected Output of the Go File 4The extra parameter is called the method’s receiver. Hence, these kinds of methods (functions) are also called receiver functions. Unlike conventional OOP languages, Go didn’t use any special name like this or self the receiver is the ordinary parameter, and you can choose it by its name.
The receiver is a copy of the literal value. The literal function can not modify the passed literal using the function. Refer to the example Go file 5 below.
